  <section id="healthcare-system">
    <h2>Healthcare System Overview</h2>
    <p>
      Colombia's healthcare quality genuinely impresses. Major cities have hospitals rivaling US facilities, doctors trained internationally, and medical costs 50-80% lower than comparable US care. Understanding the system helps you maximize both local resources and international insurance.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Top hospitals</strong> in Medellín include Hospital Pablo Tobón Uribe (internationally accredited), Clínica Las Américas, and Hospital San Vicente Fundación. In Bogotá, Fundación Santa Fe, Clínica del Country, and Hospital Universitario San Ignacio provide excellent care. These facilities have modern equipment, English-speaking staff in many departments, and direct billing with international insurers.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Medical tourism infrastructure</strong> means Colombian hospitals are experienced with international patients. Patient coordinators assist with appointments, translation, and logistics. Procedures from cardiac surgery to orthopedics to dentistry draw patients from throughout the Americas seeking quality at lower costs.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Specialist availability:</strong> Medellín and Bogotá have specialists across all fields. Appointment availability is generally better than in the US—you can often see specialists within days rather than weeks. Private/international insurance provides fastest access; EPS may have longer waits for non-urgent consultations.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Regional considerations:</strong> Healthcare quality decreases significantly outside major cities. Coastal cities like Cartagena have adequate facilities but less depth than Medellín or Bogotá. Smaller cities and rural areas require travel to major centers for serious conditions. Your insurance's evacuation coverage applies for inter-city transfers when local facilities are insufficient.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Prescription medications:</strong> Pharmacies are abundant, and many medications are cheaper than in the US. Colombian pharmacists are knowledgeable and can often recommend alternatives if specific brands aren't available. Some US medications may have different brand names or formulations—bring documentation of your prescriptions.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="costs">
    <h2>Cost Planning</h2>
    <p>
      Colombia offers excellent value, with total retirement costs significantly below comparable US lifestyle. City choice affects costs—Medellín and Bogotá cost more than secondary cities—but even the most expensive Colombian cities are affordable by international standards.
    </p>
    <ComparisonTable columns={costColumns} rows={costRows} />
    <p>
      <strong>Total monthly budget</strong> for comfortable retirement with comprehensive health coverage typically ranges from $1,800-3,200 depending on city and lifestyle. Medellín mid-range retirement runs $2,200-2,800; Bogotá similar or slightly higher; smaller cities can achieve comfortable living for $1,800-2,400.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Healthcare cost strategies:</strong> Full international insurance runs $370-750/month for seniors. Using Colombian EPS plus prepaid medicine ($150-400/month) with lighter international coverage for evacuation only can reduce total healthcare costs while maintaining comprehensive protection. The right balance depends on health status and risk tolerance.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Currency considerations:</strong> Colombia uses the peso, which fluctuates against the dollar. When the peso weakens, your dollar income buys more—Colombia becomes even more affordable. When the peso strengthens, costs rise. Most retirees find fluctuations manageable but maintaining some USD reserves provides cushion.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Emergency fund:</strong> Maintain $5,000-10,000 in accessible funds for medical deductibles, unexpected evacuation costs, and emergencies. Colombia's stability has improved dramatically, but prudent reserves remain sensible financial planning.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="faqs">
    <h2>Common Questions</h2>

    <div class="grid gap-6 md:grid-cols-2 mt-6">
      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Is Colombia safe for retirees?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">Major cities like Medellín and Bogotá have transformed dramatically and are generally safe with normal urban precautions. Expat neighborhoods have low crime. Avoid certain rural areas and use common sense. Most retirees report feeling safer than expected.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Can I rely on Colombian healthcare without international insurance?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">Many long-term residents do, using EPS plus prepaid medicine. The system is excellent for most conditions. However, rare diseases, certain advanced treatments, and complex surgeries may still benefit from evacuation options that international insurance provides.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">How good is English in Colombian healthcare?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">Major hospitals in Medellín and Bogotá have English-speaking staff in patient coordination. Many doctors speak English, especially younger ones trained internationally. Smaller facilities and administrative staff may be Spanish-only. Basic Spanish helps significantly.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">What about altitude in Medellín and Bogotá?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">Medellín (5,000 ft) rarely causes altitude issues. Bogotá (8,600 ft) can affect some people, especially those with respiratory or cardiac conditions. Most adjust within days to weeks. If altitude concerns you, stick to Medellín or coastal cities like Cartagena.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">How does the EPS system actually work?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">You enroll with an EPS provider (Sura, Sanitas recommended), pay monthly based on income, and access their network of clinics and hospitals. Coverage is comprehensive but may involve waiting lists for non-urgent care. Adding prepaid medicine provides faster access and private facilities.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Is the $900/month income requirement really enough?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">It's enough for visa qualification but tight for comfortable living with health insurance. Realistic comfortable retirement budgets start around $1,800-2,000/month. The low visa threshold makes Colombia accessible, but planning for higher actual expenses is prudent.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <CTABox
    title="Ready to Plan Your Colombia Retirement?"
    description="Get personalized quotes from insurers experienced with retirees in Colombia. Coverage complements excellent local healthcare with evacuation and international options."
    buttonText="Get Your Quotes"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
  />
</PageShell>
